Time series analysis





Introduction

The DUQ_hourly dataset contains hourly records electric power consumption volumes in MW over the time period from 2013 until 2017. The data were collected at the Duquesne power utility units in two counties in Pennsylvania, where the largest power consuming city is Pittsburg. The aim of this paper is to outline the most significant results of time series analysis performed on the dataset and predict short-term power consumption rates.

Exploratory analysis

hist(energyData$DUQ_MW, col="lightblue")

qqnorm(energyData$DUQ_MW, pch=20); qqline(energyData$DUQ_MW, col="blue")

The data displayed in the following figure is supposed to be non-independent and the TS has discrete time intervals.

ggplot(data = energyData, aes(x = Datetime, y = DUQ_MW))+
  geom_line(color = "#00AFBB", size = 0.5) + ggtitle('Duquesne Power - Consumption, 2012-2017')+
  xlab('Date') + ylab('Consumption in MW')

Yearly

Examine the specific year for better understanding of seasonality.

ggplot(data = energyData[energyData$Datetime >= '2016-01-01' & energyData$Datetime <= '2016-12-31',], aes(x = Datetime, y = DUQ_MW))+
  geom_line(color = "#00AFBB", size = 0.5) + ggtitle('Duquesne Power - Consumption, 2016')+
  xlab('Date') + ylab('Consumption in MW')

Seasonality is utterly important while analysing time series in the scope of one year. Due to large amount of observations, we may only describe the monthly seasonality from the previous plot. Starting from June until the end August the power consumption volumes remain on the high level. The lower consumption rates are observed during autumn and spring, whereas the winter period starting from mid December and finishing in late February brings strong fluctuations at higher rates.

Simple moving average

Smoothing is a way to locally aggregate data where non-systematic components compensate each other.

\[ \begin{aligned}\large Y_t=\frac{1}{2k+1}\sum_{j=-k}^k{X_{t+j}} \end{aligned} \]

plot(ma(msts_power, order=1000))

TS decomposition

Given the additive TS model

\[ \begin{aligned}\large X_t = T_t+Z_t +S_t+\epsilon_t,t=1,..,n \end{aligned} \] we may decompose the TS into the four components: trend, cycle, seasonalty and error(white noise).

mstl(msts_power2) %>% autoplot()

Three types of seasonality are represented in the plot above: daily, weekly, yearly. Each of these are calculated as following:

\[ \begin{aligned}\large \tilde{S_t} = \tilde{X_t}-\tilde{T_t} \end{aligned} \]

ACF and PACF

\[ \begin{aligned}\large \rho(k) = \frac{\gamma(k)}{\gamma(0)},k=0,1,.. \end{aligned} \]

acf(msts_power, lag.max = 200)

pacf(msts_power, lag.max = 200)

Stationarity

Strong stationarity is defined as follows: \[ \begin{aligned}\large X(t_i) \simeq X(t_i+ \tau) \end{aligned} \] \[ \begin{aligned}\large H_0:\ \gamma \neq 0 \end{aligned} \]

adf.test(msts_power, alternative = "stationary")
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  msts_power
## Dickey-Fuller = -10.856, Lag order = 35, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

The TS is stationary, though the ACF plot implies the majority of observations exceeds the boundaries of the significance interval.

Simple exponential smoothing

fc <- ses(msts_power2, h=24*36)
autoplot(fc) + autolayer(fitted(fc))

accuracy(fc$fitted, duq_test$DUQ_MW)
##                 ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE
## Test set -97.51936 313.6078 258.4307 -9.509817 17.61876
tsdisplay(residuals(fc))

ARFIMA

In an ARIMA model, the integrated part of the model includes the differencing operator (1 − B) (where B is the backshift operator) raised to an integer power. In a fractional model, the power is allowed to be fractional, with the meaning of the term identified using the following formal binomial series expansion \[ \begin{aligned}\large (1-B)^d=\sum_{k=0}^{\propto}C_d^k(-B)^k \end{aligned} \]

fitarfima <- arfima(msts_power2)
plot(forecast(fitarfima))

accuracy(fitarfima$fitted,duq_test$DUQ_MW)
##                 ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE
## Test set -97.31979 306.3955 247.7103 -9.326757 16.77583
tsdisplay(residuals(fitarfima))

LOESS(Local polynomial regression)

Forecasts of STL objects are obtained by applying a non-seasonal forecasting method to the seasonally adjusted data and re-seasonalizing using the last year of the seasonal component.

lpr_fit <- stlf(msts_power)
plot(forecast(lpr_fit))

accuracy(lpr_fit$fitted,duq_test$DUQ_MW)
##                 ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE
## Test set -97.61584 296.7804 240.7237 -9.279443 16.34963
tsdisplay(residuals(lpr_fit))
